    Page Speed Matters!

    I have finally reached the pinnacle!

    I have been tinkering with website page speed optimization for years, although never really giving it the focus that it deserved. I regularly use sites like Google Page Speed, GTMetrix.com, YSlow, and Pingdom. Over the years, with an analysis tool like Google Page Insights, most sites I built generally averaged in the mid 70s, maybe peaking at 80/100 on desktop and forget about mobile. Mobile analysis would generally range around the high 60s if not worse.

    Dont get me wrong, I cared about it and always did what I could to optimize images, etc but at the close of a project and deployment, Im generally ready to take a break. I always use the excuse, Ill get back to the optimizations later.. but of course that never happens.

    Now, page speed and micro-optimization has become an obsession.

    As of 10:05am this morning, I reached the summit of the mountain, a perfect 100/100 on Google Page Speed and an average of mid to high 90s on GTMetrix and YSlow for almost all of my personal blogs pages. My home/index page doesnt quite score as high due to having embedded pens from CodePen and some other various API calls to Twitter and LastFM. Those eat up some of my score, but for the most part are out of my control. Every other page on my site scores either 100/100 or mighty darn close.

    For those of you who dabble in page speed tweaks and enhancements, its not an easy task to get there. Its a stealthy combination of image optimization, caching, compression, and many other micro optimization techinques.

    Google defines its Top 10 requirements as:
    • Enable compression
    • Leverage browser caching
    • Optimize images
    • Minify HTML
    • Avoid landing page redirects
    • Eliminate render-blocking JavaScript and CSS in above-the-fold content
    • Minify CSS
    • Minify JavaScript
    • Prioritize visible content
    • Reduce server response time

    Its also handy to use some of the tools...

    What I Learned About GulpJS

    Some time back.. before the age of my SASS enlightment, I was writng in pure CSS, pure Javascript, no compiling, no minifying, nothing. Fast forward a few years and I had finally jumped on the SASS bandwagon, far later than I shouldve I admit. This is what got me interested in the world of task running and the need for code compiling. Id heard of GruntJS through Meetups and friends, but honestly it scared me somewhat. I wasnt quite comfortable with Javascript at that point and really much more of a GUI type guy.

    I am a frequent listener of the Shoptalk Show and during one of those episodes head them discuss an app called Codekit which could do compilation/minification of SASS, JS, etc. I downloaded it and fell in love quickly. I purchased a license and began integrating it heavily into all my projects. It was a beautiful and clean UI, solid functionality and for the most part unobtrussive to my workflow.

    I used Codekit for almost a year before I decided to feed my inner geek and give GruntJS a shot. I was getting more comfortable with Javascript and just starting to play with command line. I sat down one night and spun my wheels for several hours researching on Stack Overflow and reading blog posts about how to set it all up. After about 2 more nights of hammering away I finally produced a decent grunt.js file that I could use with my projects. Albeit there were a few hiccups switching off of Codekit, I made it work. The switch made handing off files to other developers easier as they didnt have to have a Codekit license, retain the same Codekit config, etc. They could just Git my files and run Grunt. I continuing using Grunt for about 6 months until I heard about a new kid on the block, Gulp.
